	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				HARMONY GUIDE:<BR>
<BR>
Since there seems to be some confusion, allow me to shed some light into Harmony, one of the most overlooked Druid spells I've seen.<BR>
<BR>
I spent a fair amount of time at various goblin, orc, dervish, and bandit camps, and later at the Aviaks in South Karana.  There's no more useful spell for these places than Harmony.<BR>
<BR>
Harmony is the druid's outdoor only equivalent of Calm.  It allows you to safely spell-pull one creature out of a group.<BR>
<BR>
For most predictable use, target each creature you don't want to come out and cast directly on them.<BR>
<BR>
For areas where you are around non-hostiles, the better bet is to place yourself between multiple targets, and cast Harmony on *yourself*.  Since Harmony is an &quot;AE around target&quot; effect, you can generally harmonize multiple targets with one cast.<BR>
<BR>
The other benefit of the latter method, is there is zero chance of spell resistance (in my experience).  If I am standing between an aviak rook (L20) and avocet (L30), if I cast on myself, both are calmed, even though I may not normally have been able to cast at an avocet.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, I have never seen Harmony cause a creature to attack.  By the same token, I have also never seen it resisted.<BR>
<BR>
The recent patch improved Harmony somewhat - It now lights up each creature who was successfully harmonized, provided you're close enough to see.<BR>
<BR>
Be sure to cast it on yourself once to time the effect.  I've seen a constant 45 seconds the whole time.  If you're harmonizing many creatures, you don't want harmony running out on the first couple just as you're pulling your selected victim from the pile.<BR>
<BR>
Once you pull the creature with a spell (I prefer snare), make sure the pulling path doesn't cross any other harmonized creatures, as that will almost certainly break their harmony, and you'll get more than you bargained for.<BR>
<BR>
Once that's done, it's time to DoT them and take them out for a little jog or thorn up and let them impale themselves to death on your damage shields.  (My personal favorite - killing something and realizing later that I forgot to turn on &quot;attack&quot; ;)<BR>
<BR>
Best of luck!<BR>
<BR>
Darrion Stormbringer,<BR>
24th Rank Druid of Rivervale,<BR>
Officer, The Pantheon,<BR>
Keeper of an inanely long signature,<BR>
And way too many commas,<BR>
Innoruuk
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
